\section{Historic (Taiwanese...kana?)}

If I were given the task of naming Taiwanese kana, or, perhaps better said, translating their Hokkien/Japanese name, I would have named them ``Hokkien kana''. Because, indeed, that's what they are; historically speaking, there's nothing Taiwanese about Taiwanese kana except that they can be used to write Taiwanese Hokkien. Indeed, they are not even exclusively \em{Taiwanese}, as they are also suitable for writing the Quanzhou dialect.

Taiwanese kana were invented by Japanese linguists on behalf of the imperial Japanese government, which at the time of their introduction, was pursuing a policy of \em{dÅka} (\cjk{åŒåŒ–}), meaning, ``assimilation''. The period we most remember them for today was the period of the 1930's, when they were spread primarily to teach Taiwanese people Japanese.\footnote{Chen, Chun-Hui [\cjk{é™³å›æ…§}] (June 2002); Lin, Ching-Hsiun [\cjk{æ—æ…¶å‹³}], ed. \Href[src=https://etd.lis.nsysu.edu.tw//ETD-db/ETD-search-c/view_etd?URN=etd-0730102-160424]{\cjk{``ã€Šè¨‚æ­£å°ç£åäº”éŸ³å­—æ¯è©³è§£ã€‹éŸ³ç³»ç ”ç©¶''}}. National Sun Yat-sen University Chinese Literature Department: Master's Thesis.} 

The primary person involved in their creation was the linguist Naoyoshi Ogawa [\cjk{å°å·å°šç¾©}].\footnote{Ibid, p. 19.} The first of Ogawa's works that they make a notable appearance in is the \em{Japanese--Taiwanese Daijiten} (\cjk{æ—¥å°å¤§è¾­å…¸}) of 1907.\footnote{Ibid, p. 19--20.} Another early example is a textbook from 1902, the \em{Textbook for Taiwan} (\cjk{å°æ¹¾æ•™ç§‘ç”¨æ›¸}). Ogawa continued to refine them until he published his greatest work, the two volume \em{Comprehensive Taiwaneseâ€“Japanese Dictionary} [\cjk{è‡ºæ—¥å¤§è¾­å…¸}] (1931). Indeed, it is entirely on the back of this work that modern interest in them continues, with the dictionary continuing to receive updates long after the collapse of the Japanese empire; even famed Taiwanese linguist Ã‚ng Ã›i-jÃ®n contributed substantially to an update of the dictionary in 1993, published as the \em{Minnan Classic Dictionary Collection} (\cjk{é–©å—èªç¶“å…¸è¾­æ›¸å½™ç·¨}).

Due to the high quality of this dictionary, which even informed the Taiwanese government's own \em{Dictionary of Frequently-Used Taiwan Minnan} [\cjk{è‡ºç£é–©å—èªå¸¸ç”¨è©è¾­å…¸}] (1\sup{st} ed. 2011),\footnote{``Bibliography'' [\cjk{åƒè€ƒæ›¸ç›®}]. \Href[src=https://twblg.dict.edu.tw/holodict_new/compile1_3_9_5.jsp]{\cjk{è‡ºç£é–©å—èªå¸¸ç”¨è©è¾­å…¸}}. Retrieved August 1, 2020.} Japanese learners of Hokkien continue to use Taiwanese kana even today.\footnote{For two examples of Japanese learners of Hokkien who use Taiwanese kana, see the Twitter profiles of Soaâ¿-kiÄ (\Href[src=https://twitter.com/suannkia]{@suannkia}) and Taipa (\Href[src=https://twitter.com/taipa]{@taipalogy}).} But, of course, this is not the only reason to encode Taiwanese kana; they are interesting in and of themselves, as a historical writing system with a large body of work behind it.

Even in Ogawa's time, he was not the only author; other Japanese scholars recognized the quality of his work, and many other works exist which integrate Taiwanese kana, such as the \em{Taiwan Proverb Collection} [\cjk{è‡ºç£ä¿šè«ºé›†è¦½}] (1914) and the \em{State Monopoly Bureau's Taiwanese Dictionary} [\cjk{å°ˆè³£å±€å°ç£èªå…¸}] (1923), which, unlike Ogawa's work, mixed \em{PeÌh-Åe-jÄ«} with Taiwanese kana.

In our time, besides being used as a substantial basis for the \em{Dictionary of Frequently-Used Taiwan Minnan}, Ã‚ng Ã›i-jÃ®n's version of the dictionary lives on due to a project of LÃ®m ChÃ¹n-i\|{o}k [\cjk{æ—ä¿Šè‚²}] of the Academia Sinica: \hbox{\url{taigi.fhl.net/dict}}. This impressive work is a complete digitization of the 1993 dictionary, and when you search for terms, you are given links to individual pages of it. For example, searching \cjk{\rubyA[reading=ã‚†ã‚]{å¤¢}}, meaning ``dream'', brings up \Href[src=https://taigi.fhl.net/dict/gm.php?fn=B/B0601.png]{page 555 of volume 2}, which brings up quite a detailed entry, which differentiates between frightening dreams/nightmares (\cjk{æã‚ã—ã„å¤¢}) and merely bad dreams (\cjk{æ‚ªã„å¤¢}); between being told about a dream (\cjk{å¤¢ã®å‘Šã‚’å—ã‘ã‚‹}) from dream interpretation (\cjk{å¤¢åˆ¤æ–­}):
