\section{On naming}

Finally, I will explain my reasoning for why I am requesting the glyph names I am requesting. I have very deliberately chosen not to include a reference to Taiwan in either the names of the characters or the name of the requested block. In China, even the word Taiwan is politically sensitive, as is the period of Japanese rule. Further, Taiwanese kana write the Hokkien language, which is also spoken in mainland China. Indeed, the Quanzhou dialect, historically named the ``Chinchew dialect'', gets its name from the city of Quanzhou (\cjk{æ³‰å·å¸‚}). Second of all, the Taiwanese kana were used occasionally in imperial Japan in the linguistic study of other Chinese languages, though the vast majority of surviving sources and modern use is in/for Hokkien.

The UTC should be aware of this issue when deciding on naming. My proposal originally asked the UTC to name the characters \em{Hokkien}. Eiso Chan, however, thought that \em{Min Nan} would be better, as this is the name used by ISO 639--3, and submitted the comment document L2/20-233. I strongly agree, and have revised the character names in my proposal accordingly.

\section{On shakuhachi notation}

The \em{shakuhachi} (\cjk{\rubyA[reading=ã—ã‚ƒã]{å°º}\rubyA[reading=ã¯ã¡]{å…«}}) is a traditional Japanese instrument, which looks similar to a flute. It has a traditional notation scheme known as \em{shakuhachi gakufu} (\cjk{å°ºå…«\rubyA[reading=ãŒã]{æ¥½}\rubyA[reading=ãµ]{è­œ}}).

As seen below,\footnote{Via Tenzan Yamada (\cjk{å±±ç”°å…¸å±±}): \Href[src=https://ameblo.jp/yamadatenzan/entry-12401910405.html]{\cjk{æƒ…ç†±å¤§é™¸ã®å°ºå…«è­œ}}.} in \em{shakuhachi}, the combining characters mentioned in this proposal do not combine the same way in vertical writing. They combine on the right, as is more common in CJK contexts.

\center{\img[src=shakuhachi.png,height=25%ph]}

I agree with Eiso Chan's recommendations in L2/20-233. I am hopeless when it comes to musical subjects, so a more complete \em{shakuhachi} proposal will not be forthcoming from me, and it is out of the scope of this proposal. However, I immediately understand the wisdom of a registered OpenType feature such as \code{skhc}. As far as Unicode is concerned, Chan's recommended changes to \code{NameList.txt} and UAX#50 are in my opinion sound.

